      <div class='static-page__row'>
        <h3 class='static-page__subtitle static-page__subtitle--sinai'>St. Catherine's Monastery and Its Library</h3>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            Located in Egypt’s Sinai Peninsula, the Orthodox “Sacred Monastery of the God-Trodden Mount Sinai,” commonly known as St. Catherine’s Monastery of the Sinai, is one of the world’s oldest monasteries and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. In the 6th century the Byzantine Emperor Justinian founded the Monastery and built it to approximately its current form, though monks had occupied the site by the 4th century. From the 4th century until today, the monks of Sinai have celebrated the Orthodox liturgy in unbroken continuity and have welcomed pilgrims from around the world, which accounts for the diversity of languages represented in its library.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            Protected by its remote location on the Sinai Peninsula and its centuries-old bond with its Muslim neighbors, the Monastery preserves one of the world’s most important libraries. Its 4,559 manuscripts date from the 4th to the 19th century and are surprisingly diverse. Containing texts in 13 languages, they cover a range of genres, including books of the Bible, liturgy, hagiography, patristics, spirituality, and history, as well as a small but important number of classical poetic, scientific and philosophical texts. The Monastery’s collection of Greek manuscripts is considered to be second only to that of the Vatican, and the Monastery preserves arguably the most important collection of early Syriac and Christian Arabic manuscripts. Together the manuscripts of St. Catherine’s Monastery provide unparalleled evidence for the literature and history of Christians in the Eastern Mediterranean and shed light on the relations between Christian and Muslim communities.
          </p>
      </div>

      <div class='static-page__row'>
          <h3 class='static-page__subtitle static-page__subtitle--sinai'>Manuscript Digitization and Online Access</h3>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            St. Catherine’s Monastery of the Sinai, EMEL, and the UCLA Library are now collaborating to digitize the Monastery’s unparalleled manuscript collection and to make the resulting images accessible in an online, searchable digital library. In Phase One (February 2018 through spring 2022), EMEL is digitizing the Monastery’s Arabic and Syriac manuscripts (1,172 codices / 400,000 pages). In Phase Two, EMEL will digitize the Monastery’s collections of manuscripts in Greek, Georgian, Slavonic, and other languages (3,387 codices / 1.1 million pages).
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            The UCLA Library is creating an online, searchable digital library of the manuscripts that will enable users to search metadata collected from a variety of sources, identify manuscripts of interest, and then zoom in and pan across images and compare images of different manuscripts. Projects to undertake new scholarly cataloging of the manuscripts are in the planning stages but are beyond the scope of the current digitization project. Complete sets of the collected images are deposited at the Monastery in the Sinai, at the Monastery’s Athens office, and with the UCLA Library.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            By these means, the Sinai Manuscripts Digital Library will preserve the contents of the Monastery’s unique manuscript library and enable scholars and interested persons around the world to study high-quality images of the manuscripts and add to our knowledge of the Monastery’s library and its history.
          </p>
      </div>

      <div class='static-page__row'>
        <h3 class='static-page__subtitle static-page__subtitle--sinai'>Digitization Standards and Methods</h3>
        <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
          The project has installed four digitization workstations in a large room graciously provided by the Monastery and recently renovated by the Saint Catherine Foundation. Digitization personnel undertake six four-week imaging sessions annually. Captured images range from 600 to 1,100 ppi depending on the size of manuscript and meet or exceed relevant standards.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            The first consideration when digitizing medieval manuscripts, especially in the low-humidity conditions of the Sinai, is the safe handling of the manuscripts. To accommodate manuscripts in different states of preservation, the project is operating two different materials handling solutions.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            <i>The Preservation Book Cradle (PBC)</i> by Stokes Imaging (Austin, TX) is designed to support fragile parchment codices. It uses computer-controlled motors to rotate the spine of a fragile codex, following the natural movement of the codex as its pages are turned.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
            <i>Modified BC100</i> by Digital Transitions (New York) supports the efficient digitization of stable codices by using two cameras to capture both pages of an open book simultaneously. To make the BC100 appropriate for medieval manuscripts, EMEL introduced a customized frame that restrains fragile folios with flexible tabs.
          </p>
          <p class='static-page__text static-page__text--sinai'>
